		<div class="mx-auto mt-20 w-full max-w-screen-xl bg-primary-50 px-10 py-10 text-black">
			<h1 class="mb-8 text-center text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl">
				Understanding How Genes Affect Cancer
			</h1>
			<ExpandableText>
				<div slot="initial" class="prose-lg mx-auto">
					<p>
						Human bodies are intricate systems composed of trillions of cells, each containing DNA,
						the fundamental genetic material. DNA is organized into genes, which serve as the
						instruction manual for our bodies’ functions, influencing growth, development,
						metabolism, and reproduction. Each human possesses approximately 20,000 genes, each with
						a specific role to play. Among these genes are tumor suppressor genes. Tumor suppressor
						genes normally function to regulate cell growth, repair DNA damage, and promote
						apoptosis (programmed cell death). Mutations that inactivate tumor suppressor genes can
						result in loss of these regulatory functions, allowing cells to evade growth controls
						and survive despite genetic damage. This can significantly increase the risk of cancer
						development. On the other hand, oncogenes are mutated forms of normal genes
						(proto-oncogenes) that promote cell growth and division. When activated by mutations,
						oncogenes can drive excessive cell proliferation, leading to tumor formation.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div slot="expanded" class="prose-lg mx-auto">
					<p>
						Genetic mutations contributing to cancer can be broadly categorized into inherited
						mutations and acquired mutations. Inherited mutations are present in germline cells and
						can be passed down through generations, significantly increasing the risk of certain
						types of cancer within families. Acquired mutations, on the other hand, develop over a
						person’s lifetime and are often associated with environmental factors such as tobacco
						smoke, UV radiation, or exposure to carcinogenic chemicals. These mutations accumulate
						in somatic cells (non-germline cells) and can lead to the initiation and progression of
						cancer.
					</p>
					<p>
						Gene mutations, whether inherited or acquired, can disrupt normal cellular functions,
						leading to uncontrolled cell growth characteristic of cancer. Therefore, understanding
						these genetic mutations is crucial for identifying individuals at risk and developing
						personalized approaches to cancer prevention and treatment.
					</p>
				</div>
			</ExpandableText>
		</div>
	</div>

